== SOURCE

https://www.genengnews.com/news/deep-learning-ai-accurately-predicts-and-diagnoses-alzheimers-disease/

== AGENT

Boston University School of Medicine

== GOAL

Development and validation of an interpretable deep learning framework for Alzheimer’s disease classification.

== DATA

The model was trained using clinically diagnosed Alzheimer’s disease and cognitively normal subjects from the Alzheimer’s Disease Neuroimaging Initiative (ADNI) dataset (n = 417) and validated on three independent cohorts: the Australian Imaging, Biomarker and Lifestyle Flagship Study of Ageing (AIBL) (n = 382), the Framingham Heart Study (n = 102), and the National Alzheimer’s Coordinating Center (NACC) (n = 582).

== METHODS

An Fully Convolutional Network (FCN) was designed to input a registered volumetric MRI scan and output the Alzheimer’s disease class probability at every location. During the training process, the model was saved when it achieved the lowest error. After FCN training, single volumetric MRI scans were forwarded to obtain complete arrays of disease probabilities, referred to as disease probability maps. Once trained, the process of obtaining disease probability maps from test cases took 1 second

== RESULTS

Performance of the model that used the multimodal inputs was consistent across datasets, with a mean area under curve values of 0.996, 0.974, 0.876, and 0.954 for the ADNI study, AIBL, Framingham Heart Study, and NACC datasets, respectively.

An international team of expert neurologists was then asked to perform the task of detecting Alzheimer’s disease on the same set of cases. In this head-to-head comparison, the algorithm model performed slightly better than the average neurologist.

The research team was optimistic about the results of this study and noted that it has broad implications for expanding the use of neuroimaging data such as MRI scans to accurately detect the risk of Alzheimer’s disease at the point of care.

